content.description: Pull up the slab on the far right side of the boulder, passing an undercling. One of the easier problems on the boulder.
content.location: Far right side of the boulder.

content.description: In between the flake and the dyno is a line of thin slippery holds. Smedge your way up tiny polished edges with small hands and reach up for polished sloper at the lip. The flake is off. Way harder than the lieback, this is a great one to "polish" your slab skill.

A silly but fun variation. Lieback the lieback the other way, leaning off right and using the footholds on the original as your handholds and the lieback itself for your feet, as well as a few tiny holds out right. Finish the same as the original.
content.protection: One pad. Back in the day it was one scrap of carpet

content.description:
[Meant to be a harder start to the Flake]

Start with a hand match on the upwards facing flake and your left foot on a lower chip. Mantle up and bring your right foot over to a small ledge and move into a thumb press onto the main flake (the best spot for your thumb is on the lower end of the flake in a spot roughly the size of a penny). Then work up the flake as normal.

null
In between the crack and the flake is an obvious peaked mantleshelf. Grab it, mantle, and reach up for inobvious edges above. Harder than it looks.

The namesake of Lieback Rock.

Lieback up a right facing rail where the rock splits from pink to grey.  Get up to a finger pocket undercling.  Follow undercling flake around right and then finish up the seam to the top.

Classic.  Feels more like an actual trad route than a boulder since it is so long and varied.  Some start on the right side of the rail for added difficulty.
content.protection: Pad and somebody to move it.  Crux is start up to undercling so a pad at the start only is helpful.
content.location: Center to rigt side of Lieback Rock.

content.description: Work your way up and then dyno to a large jug.  Then up to the top.  Can be done static as well but it takes more skill.
content.location: Just left of the lieback rail at the start of the lieback.

climbs.name: Funky Like a Monkey (aka Lieback Rock Traverse)

content.description:
A traverse of lieback rock. Start at the lieback, and traverse left through slippery slabby moves, staying low. When you reach the flake, the face becomes overhung. Make some powerful gymnastic moves to the mantleshelf, then make a hand traverse across it with no feet. A final hard move gets you into the fingercrack. Finish up it.

For a harder variation, start all the way around right and up from the lieback. Traverse left, staying as low as you can. This adds a hard, slippery, thin, downclimbing slab crux to the problem, and bumps the grade at least one higher, but detracts from the overall quality somewhat.
This is the obvious left facing flake in between the dyno problem and the fingercrack. Makes some tricky 5.9ish moves on edges and sidepulls up into the flake and an easier topout.
A short positive crack found on the left side of the boulder
Desperate slab climbing on tiny holds, to the left of the other unknown slab and right of the lieback
content.protection: An old manky carpet scrap, or if you prefer, a crashpad
content.location: A few feet right of the lieback
